        <tr> 
          <td height="15">&nbsp;</td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td><textarea name="textarea" cols="40" rows="30" readonly>Image 592

The hexagonal font at the church of St Botolph, Trunch, North Norfolk is guarded by a glorious font canopy (very late fifteenth century) of remarkable quality, and a very rare survival. The canopy is in two stages and is encrusted with vegetable decoration that retains some of its original polychrome colouring. The lower stage has six posts decorated with foliage trails: vine, lily and thistle are recognizable, together with twisted branches. This stage ends in a fan-like vault, while the upper stage has eight hanging vaulted canopies which are too broad to have contained only one figure each and seem originally to have been connected with the posts below by flying buttresses. The canopy is surmounted by a crotcheted ogee top. The flamboyant original effect of this canopy, once highly polychrome and encrusted with decoration, underlines the significance of the font and, with it, of baptism.

Pevsner and Wilson 1997, p.700</textarea></td>
